I'd recommend going through the ["using AllenNLP in your repo" tutorial](https://github.com/allenai/allennlp/blob/master/tutorials/getting_started/using_in_your_repo.md), which is an explanation of the code you need to write to use AllenNLP to write models for your own task.  The only thing you should have to change there is the default tokenizer.  To do that, you add some parameters for the tokenizer [here](https://github.com/allenai/allennlp/blame/2a0804e77e34f04a64fc4d0e005185f2e50e0e3f/tutorials/getting_started/using_in_your_repo.md#L479-L483).  Your parameters might look something like this:

```json
"dataset_reader": {
  "type": "s2_papers",
  "tokenizer": {
    "type": "word",
    "word_splitter": {
      "type": "spacy",
      "language": "xx"
    }
  }
}
```

The spacy `xx` language is their "multi-language" model (they don't have a Swedish model).  You'll need to run `python -m spacy download xx` to download the model before this will work.

Instead of using spacy, you could also just tokenize words using nltk, or our heuristic "simple" tokenizer, or any other available [`WordSplitter`](https://github.com/allenai/allennlp/blob/master/allennlp/data/tokenizers/word_splitter.py) (or one you write yourself for Swedish!).  You would just change the `word_splitter` parameters accordingly.

